metadata.name: Continuum #129
metadata.description:
This project is the culmination of many generative art experiments I have run throughout 2022. It relies heavily on the random walks through color and space techniques I have been working with, but also introduces other elements related to 2D and 3D rotation, framing and grains.

Continuum began as an abstract composition made up of a set of interacting elements against a background. This is still true. However, in my own mind, I have come to consider many Continuum pieces as peculiar, stylized observations of massive futuristic spacial, or quantum, constructions. Maybe even involving a wormhole through the fabric of space-time for some civilization well past 1 on the Kardashev scale. At the center is an erratic crystalline form, which is fed by power trains, and all around is a massive multicolored rotating containment structure.

Aside from the standard, inverse, threshold and washed types, the most defining trait of each composition is the “Back Style” which relates to a point of construction, activity or deconstruction of these structures. This is further refined by the panel style, the panel density and the rotation level. The other traits largely relate to color variability and aesthetics. 

This work has been coded using p5.js, and half of all royalties from the primary, and secondary, sales are assigned to the processing foundation.

Press s to download a 2400x2400 pixel image.

This work is licensed under the Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial 4.0 International License.

metadata.name: Fictional Cityscapes #50
metadata.description:
Some of the most stunning, and beloved, images are large cities, viewed from afar at the right angle, and preferably with some water in front. 

This project comes from my experiments with line art, and is slightly inspired by Hevey's amazing Dencity drop, which is on a different level to most generative art. 

The cities here are based on some fictional tower architecture and some unusual skies.

metadata.name: change is life #87
metadata.description:
Change in nature comes as a smooth routine. The color change takes over the leaves until they fall off. And eventually green Will reappear.
It is not so for humans.
This collection looks up to nature and embraces change. At some point in life, an unexpected crisis may occur, yet it can bring new opportunities. Welcome the learning process. Embrace the growth. Face life and live.

metadata.name: Plottable Mountain Moons #371
metadata.description:
What makes this NFT have value? not only the digital is cool but it is the recipe to a plottable. Owning this NFT confers the right to request a physical plot (21cm square). @greweb will ask extra fees for this service => https://greweb.me/plots/nft

Full article: https://greweb.me/2021/12/plottable-mountain-moons

Plottable Mountain Moons generalize many explorations done this year. There are 13 inks, 9 different shape primitives with recursion, various intensity, and frequencies of noise,... and many rare cases to discover!

Digital and Physical art, hybrid and decoupled:
- The art is published via a digital NFT on Tezos blockchain – its digital representation simulates fountain pen inks drawing on paper with animated effects.
- Token to the physical world: owning each NFT confer the power to request the related physical plot: https://greweb.me/plots/nft

@greweb – 2021 – tech: WebGL + Rust + WASM – CC BY-SA 4.0 https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0/

metadata.name: fx(mash) #214
metadata.description:
fx(mash) is my humble contribution to celebrating #fxhashturnsone

This series is based on a simple algorithm - lines of a random length are drawn on a square grid until the grid is full.

I have added a variety of features based on some of my favorite fxhash projects and a few special guests.

This collection is intentionally diverse and disorderly, that's a nice way of saying I only had a short period of time following the release of Acequia. As a result, some of the outputs might be weird, messy, or even bordering on broken (if you get one of the latter please let me know and I'll reimburse you).

Despite being a bit rough around the edges, I hope fx(mash) reflects some measure of my love for the fxhash community. If you're feeling kind, then perhaps it even harks back to the experimental early days :)

The last year has been an incredible journey, thank you for letting me be a part of our story so far.

Controls (in live view):

- Press [s] to save the current image
- Press [g] to toggle grain
- Press [h] for a high-res output

Beta Controls (in live view, definitely not fully tested):

- Press [p] to start/pause animation
- Press [i] to slow down animation
- Press [o] to speed up animation

All primary sales go to Savepakistan.


Acknowledgements:

fx(mash) uses Gorilla Sun's grain implementation, a big thanks to him and meezwhite for a great article that is well worth supporting https://www.fxhash.xyz/article/all-about-that-grain

metadata.name: 8x8 Pixel Creatures #52
metadata.description:
Pixel art is a highly relevant art form, which rarely gets the kudos it deserves from the wider art world. 

I wanted to include some small pixel art creations in another project I was working on. However, I got a bit carried away, and ended up creating a pixel creature generator.

I came to like these little pixel creatures, so I decided to share them, and give them a life on FxHash - I hope you like them too. 

There are a bunch of variations, and a reasonable chance one or two styles may never be minted, so mint away, and I hope you get a rare one. Also, minters get a share in future royalties of their mints, which may be cool in any reality where they become popular one day.

I'll probably reference these guys on other relevant art I produce, when it seems appropriate.

Coded in p5js.
